9":"1569","1502":"1502","1424":"1424","1500":"1500","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","ABT 1496":"okolo 1496","1497":"1497","1496":"1496","1430":"1430","After 1497":"po 1497","Norwich, Norfolk, England":"Norwich, Norfolk, Anglie, United Kingdom","Chediston, East Suffolk, England":"Chediston, Suffolk, Anglie, United Kingdom","of Chediston, Suffolkshire, England":"Chediston, Suffolk, Anglie, United Kingdom","Ipswich, Suffolk, England":"Ipswich, Suffolk, Anglie","Chediston, Suffolk, England":"Chediston, Suffolk, Anglie"},"da":{"1424–1502":"1424–1502","1430–1502":"1430–1502","1496–Male":"1496–Afdød","1497–Male":"1497–Afdød","–1569":"–1569","1400–1500":"1400–1500","1404–Female":"1404–Afdød","1404":"1404","1569":"1569","1502":"1502","1424":"1424","1500":"1500","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","ABT 1496":"omkring 1496","1497":"1497","1496":"1496","1430":"1430","After 1497":"efter 1497","Norwich, Norfolk, England":"Norwich, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","Chediston, East Suffolk, England":"Chediston, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","of Chediston, Suffolkshire, England":"Chediston, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Ipswich, Suffolk, England":"Ipswich, Suffolk, England","Chediston, Suffolk, England":"Chediston, Suffolk, England"},"nl":{"1424–1502":"1424–1502","1430–1502":"1430–1502","1496–Male":"1496–Overleden","1497–Male":"1497–Overleden","–1569":"–1569","1400–1500":"1400–1500","1404–Female":"1404–Overleden","1404":"1404","1569":"1569","1502":"1502","1424":"1424","1500":"1500","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","ABT 1496":"circa 1496","1497":"1497","1496":"1496","1430":"1430","After 1497":"na 1497","Norwich, Norfolk, England":"Norwich, Norfolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Chediston, East Suffolk, England":"Chediston, Suffolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","of Chediston, Suffolkshire, England":"Chediston, Suffolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Ipswich, Suffolk, England":"Ipswich, Suffolk, England","Chediston, Suffolk, England":"Chediston, Suffolk, England"},"en":{"1424–1502":"1424–1502","1430–1502":"1430–1502","1496–Male":"1496–Deceased","1497–Male":"1497–Deceased","–1569":"–1569","1400–1500":"1400–1500","1404–Female":"1404–Deceased","1404":"1404","1569":"1569","1502":"1502","1424":"1424","1500":"1500","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","ABT 1496":"about 1496","1497":"1497","1496":"1496","1430":"1430","After 1497":"after 1497","Norwich, Norfolk, England":"Norwich, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","Chediston, East Suffolk, England":"Chediston, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","of Chediston, Suffolkshire, England":"Chediston, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Ipswich, Suffolk, England":"Ipswich, Suffolk, England","Chediston, Suffolk, England":"Chediston, Suffolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Claxton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of various places called Claxton, for example in County Durham, Norfolk, and Yorkshire, or from Long Clawson (Leicestershire). All are derived from an English genitive form of the Old Norse personal name <i>Klakkr</i> (see   Clack  ) + Old English <i>tūn</i> ‘settlement’."],"variants":[{"name":"Clack","meanings":["English:","from the Old English personal name <i>Clacc</i> or its Old Norse (Danish) cognate <i>Klak</i>. As a personal name this is from a word meaning ‘lump’ and may have been used as a nickname for a large or thickset man.","possibly sometimes from a derivative of Middle English <i>clakken</i> ‘to rattle, clatter’, denoting a chatterer, alternatively, perhaps a miller, from the clack or clatter of his mill, or a bellringer."]},{"name":"Cluxton","meanings":["English: variant of   Claxton  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Clawson","meanings":["English: variant of   Claxton  .","Americanized form of North German, Danish, and Norwegian   Clausen  ,   Claussen  , or   Klausen  , and also of their Dutch cognates, such as <b>Claassen</b> or <b>Klaassen</b>, patronymics from short forms of the local equivalents of the personal name   Nicholas  . Compare   Clauson  ."]},{"name":"Claxon","meanings":["English (Essex): variant of   Claxton  . This name is absent from the medieval record, and is therefore unlikely to be a patronymic from the medieval personal name <i>Clak</i> + <i>son</i>."]}]},{"name":"Hammond","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from the Middle English, Old French personal name <i>Ha(i)mon</i>, the oblique case form of the ancient Germanic <i>Ha(i)mo</i>, a short form of various compound names beginning with <i>haim</i> ‘home’. It frequently developed excrescent <i>-d</i>, giving <i>Hamond</i>, <i>Haimund</i>, and <i>Hawmond</i>. Alternatively, the name could derive from the Middle English personal name <i>Hamund</i> (Old Norse <i>Hámundr</i>, composed of the elements <i>hár</i> ‘high’ + <i>mund</i> ‘protection’), which may have been used in Normandy and in 12th-century eastern England, but the former explanation is more likely. The surname was sometimes confused with   Almond   and   Ammon  .","English: in the Bradford area of Yorkshire, the name is a shortened form of <b>Ormondroyd</b>, formerly <i>Hamondesrode</i>, from a lost place in Birstall (Yorkshire), named with the Middle English (Old French) personal name <i>Hamon</i> (1 above) + Middle English <i>roid</i>, a southern Yorkshire pronunciation of Old English <i>rod</i> ‘clearing’.","Irish: generally an importation from England, but occasionally an adopted name for <b>Mac Ámoinn</b>, see   McCammon  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Hammonds","meanings":["English (Shropshire and Staffordshire): variant of   Hammond  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Almond","meanings":["Hebrew: Hidden"]},{"name":"Hammett","meanings":["English (southwestern England, especialy Devon): from the Middle English personal name <i>Hamet</i>, a pet form of ancient Germanic <i>Hamo</i> (see   Hammond   1)."]},{"name":"Hamon","meanings":["Pronounced ‘<b>ay</b>-mon’ Anglicized spelling of Irish <i>Éamon(n)</i> or <i>Éaman(n)</i>, Irish forms of   Edmund .  Although it still has an essentially Irish flavour, the name was popularized throughout Britain in the 1950s due to the fame of the broadcaster  Eamon Andrews  (  1922–87 )."]},{"name":"Hamlin","meanings":["English and Irish: of Norman origin, from the Norman French and Middle English personal name <i>Hamelin</i>, a double diminutive of <i>Hamo</i> (see   Hammond  ).","French: variant of   Hamelin   and, in North America, (also) an altered form of this.","Americanized form of Finnish <b>Hämäläinen</b> (see   Hamalainen  )."]},{"name":"Hampson","meanings":["The Greek form of the Scripture name, which Simonis translates, 'sol eximius,' i.e. illustrious sun; the Rev. A. Jones 'splendid sun,' i.e. great joy and felicity; Tregelles, ' solar, like the sun; ' and Fuerstius, ' sonnenahnlicher ' that is, one who resembles the sun (from shemesh, the sun)."]},{"name":"Haimes","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Yacov, Yosef.","English: variant, with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>, of <b>Haime</b>, of Norman origin, from the Old French personal name <i>Haim</i> (ancient Germanic <i>Haimo</i>, from <i>haim-</i> ‘home’), often Latinized as <i>Hamo</i>. Compare   Hammond  .","Americanized form of some similar (like-sounding) Jewish surname."]},{"name":"Hammon","meanings":["English (Middlesex and Ken): variant of   Hammond  ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":31,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Hammond Claxton was born in 1424, in Chediston, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom, his father, William Claxton III, Esq, was 25 and his mother, Unknown Stafford, was 20. He had at least 2 sons and 1 daughter with Alice Cockett. He died in 1502, in Ipswich, Suffolk, England, at the age of 78."},"et":{"1424–1502":"1424–1502","1430–1502":"1430–1502","1496–Male":"1496–Surnud","1497–Male":"1497–Surnud","–1569":"–1569","1400–1500":"1400–1500","1404–Female":"1404–Surnud","1404":"1404","1569":"1569","1502":"1502","1424":"1424","1500":"1500","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","ABT 1496":"umbes 1496","1497":"1497","1496":"1496","1430":"1430","After 1497":"pärast 1497","Norwich, Norfolk, England":"Norwich, Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Chediston, East Suffolk, England":"Chediston, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","of Chediston, Suffolkshire, England":"Chediston, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Ipswich, Suffolk, England":"Ipswich, Suffolk, England","Chediston, Suffolk, England":"Chediston, Suffolk, England"},"fi":{"1424–1502":"1424–1502","1430–1502":"1430–1502","1496–Male":"1496–Kuollut","1497–Male":"1497–Kuollut","–1569":"–1569","1400–1500":"1400–1500","1404–Female":"1404–Kuollut","1404":"1404","1569":"1569","1502":"1502","1424":"1424","1500":"1500","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","ABT 1496":"noin 1496","1497":"1497","1496":"1496","1430":"1430","After 1497":"1497 jälkeen","Norwich, Norfolk, England":"Norwich, Norfolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Chediston, East Suffolk, England":"Chediston, Suffolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","of Chediston, Suffolkshire, England":"Chediston, Suffolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Ipswich, Suffolk, England":"Ipswich, Suffolk, England","Chediston, Suffolk, England":"Chediston, Suffolk, England"},"fr":{"1424–1502":"1424–1502","1430–1502":"1430–1502","1496–Male":"1496–Décédé","1497–Male":"1497–Décédé","–1569":"–1569